Introduction

In 1837, a family well-established for generations in a rural German village sold their mill, picked up roots, and emigrated to America. When they crossed the Atlantic, Johannes and Katherina Bauer were each about 50 years old, and were joined by their seven living children ranging in age from seven to 25 years. The family settled in the rural town of Tiverton, Ohio. Over five generations the descendants spread throughout much of the United States.

The story of this family is presented in two volumes:

Volume 1: A Family Story portrays the family life in Germany, why they chose to emigrate, their voyage to America, their new life in rural Ohio, and what became of their descendants over the generations.

Available in pdf format at https://archive.org/details/bauerkleinfamilyvol1

Volume 2: Descendants Listing (this volume) provides a list of the descendants with their essential life events and relationships.

Available in pdf format at https://archive.org/details/bauerkleinfamilyvol2

Ancestry.com serves as the repository for this Bauer family tree. Anyone can access the online tree as described in Volume 1, section "Online Family Tree at Ancestry.com." Once you have a free or paid account you can access Johannes "John" Bauer, patriarch of this family tree, with this link.

The online family tree includes much more information than found in this listing, including:

  • photographs and stories of many individuals
  • obituaries, and newspaper articles and clippings
  • census records and images, showing where people lived during their lives
  • occupations, military records, birth/death/marriage certificates, and other records
  • many other family relatives, including cousins and spouses' families
  • ability to browse the family tree.

I have striven for diligence in establishing the relationships of married couples, and of children to parents. In general, I have established relationships only where there is substantial evidence based on reliable or multiple sources. The sources for life events and relationships are all included in the Ancestry.com tree.

Some facts are qualified with "possible match," indicating uncertainty. For example, the following sentence indicates that it's uncertain if the associated death record applies to this person, and thus it's uncertain if the death date and place are correct:

"He died on 16 Mar 1965 in Red Cloud, Webster, Nebraska (POSSIBLE MATCH: Red Cloud is about 230 miles from Knox County, Nebraska)."

 

Not all descendants in the Ancestry.com tree are included in this listing. The Ancestry.com tree includes some possible descendants with only speculative records or relationships—such persons are not included here. As well, those born after 1980 were generally excluded from the listing, unless requested to be included by themselves or their close relatives.

Volume 1 includes the following sections with detailed information relevant to this descendants listing:

  • Conventions for Names, Locations, and Dates
  • Information Sources and Possible Errors
  • Where to Submit Comments, Corrections, Additions
  • Online Family Tree at Ancestry.com
  • Appendix 1: Ancestors and Cousins of Johannes Bauer
  • Appendix 9: How the Listing Of Descendants and their Statistics Were Generated.

Conventions

Numbering Scheme

As shown in the example below, each descendant is listed with the lineage of ancestors leading back to the family patriarch, Johannes "John" Bauer. Where a descendant's children are listed, person identifiers are shown only for those descendants that have children.

 

Descendant Names

Variations in the spelling of names was common, even in official documents, up to the early 1900s. Where multiple spellings were possible, the most-used spelling from early in a person's life is generally used. For example, Johannes and Katherina's first son, Jacob Bauer, was often referred to as Jacob "Bower" as an adult in census records and legal documents. Jacob's children are all listed herein with the surname "Bower".

Women are listed by their birth (maiden) names.

Unknown names are shown as "______", frequently for maiden names.

Location Names

All locations in the United States follow the convention of: Town, County, State.

For example:

Coshocton, Ohio= Coshocton County, Ohio
Coshocton, Coshocton, Ohio= Coshocton City in Coshocton County, Ohio
Kansas City, , Missouri= Kansas City, county unknown, Missouri

 

To better reflect the historical context, location names are for the time of the recorded events. Therefore, a person born in Kansas in 1860 would have a birth location of "Kansas Territory," since Kansas became a state in 1861. Many counties and towns have changed their boundaries or names over time. I have tried to use the correct names for the times of recorded events, adding the current name where needed for clarity.

Event Dates

The accuracy of the dates provided is only as good as the sources from which they were determined. When different sources had different dates (not unusual), I made every effort to use the date of the most reliable source(s). For example, a birth date on a death certificate would generally take precedence over a birth date on a headstone.

Abbreviations

Common abbreviations include:

b.born
m.married
d.died
abtabout
probprobably

Marriage Order

Marriages are sometimes listed in the wrong order, which is unfortunately how they were output from the Family Tree Maker software. For example, you may see:

She married (1) RAY M DOUGLAS in Apr‑1952 in Ordway, Crowley, Colorado.

She married (2) ELWAY M GORDON on 18‑Sep‑1923 in Watson, Shawnee, Kansas. He was born about 1882 in Kansas.
